I"Ÿ<p>With revealjs outlined in a <a href="/2020/01/11/revealjs-for-linguistics-part-2-basic-presentations/">previous post</a>, with its pros and cons outlined there, now I will outline how to build a basic slideshow.</p>

<h2 id="installation">Installation</h2>

<p>In order to use reveal.js, you need to download the source files at the <a href="https://github.com/hakimel/reveal.js/">Gihhub repository</a>.
If you have a github account already, you can fork the repo or download the source files</p>

<h2 id="basic-elements">Basic elements</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Slides are contained within <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;section&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;</code> tags.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;section&gt;</code> elements can be nested, in which case you create a vertical slide underneath the current one. This is useful when you have an after-point to the current slide, or you want to contain all slides underneath sections (like a paper).</li>
  <li>Unordered lists are created with <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;ul&gt;...&lt;/ul&gt;</code></li>
  <li>Ordered list are created with <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;ol&gt;...&lt;/ol&gt;</code></li>
  <li>In both list types, <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;li&gt;...&lt;/li&gt;</code> introduce list elements.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="incremental-reveal">Incremental reveal</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Incremental uncover of elements is handled by putting <code class="highlighter-rouge">class="fragment"</code> within the elements:</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-html highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nt">&lt;ul&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>This is an unordered list.<span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;li</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"fragment"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>This element will be uncovered by advancing the presentation<span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;li</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"fragment"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>And then this one will<span class="nt">&lt;/ul&gt;</span>
<span class="nt">&lt;/ul&gt;</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
